# Cursor Rules for this project

## Bug-fix protocol

When there is a bug or error:
1. Cursor must first attempt to fix it autonomously by reading the error, locating the root cause, and applying a fix — without asking the user first.
2. Only if Cursor cannot resolve the issue after 2 attempts should the user consult Claude (in Claude.ai, the AI advisor outside Cursor) for guidance.
3. Never ask the user to manually edit code to fix bugs — always apply the fix in the editor.
4. Always verify the fix works by checking for remaining errors after each attempt.

## Root cause first, code second

Before changing any code:
1. Read the relevant file(s) in full. Do not guess.
2. Identify the root cause and state it clearly in plain English.
3. Only then write the fix. No "patch on top of patch" style edits.
4. Delete conflicting old code rather than leaving multiple coexisting logic paths.

If a bug is not resolved after 2 attempts, stop patching and re-read the entire file from scratch before making a third change.

## Forbidden patterns

- Modifying code without reading it first
- Adding new variables alongside conflicting old ones (creates dual-source-of-truth bugs)
- Using useMemo/useCallback computed objects as useEffect dependencies (causes infinite loops)
- Hardcoding paddingTop: 56/64/70 — always use useSafeAreaInsets() instead
- Hardcoding hex colors — always import from lib/theme.js
- Hardcoding spacing numbers — always use values from Spacing in lib/theme.js

## Design system rules

- All buttons that trigger primary actions must use components/PrimaryButton.js
- All colors must come from Colors in lib/theme.js (no inline hex values)
- All spacing must come from Spacing in lib/theme.js (xs/sm/md/lg/xl/xxl)
- All radii must come from Radius in lib/theme.js (small/medium/large/button/pill)
- Every screen must wrap content with useSafeAreaInsets() — never hardcode top padding

## Git workflow reminders

- After every completed feature, remind the user to commit via terminal (not Cursor's "Keep" button)
- The 5-command pattern: branch → commit → push → merge → tag
- Before any major change, create a feature branch first

## Communication style

- Reply in Chinese (the user is a Chinese-speaking solo developer)
- Use the simplest possible language — assume no technical background
- Provide copy-paste-ready instructions for the terminal when relevant
- Make minimal changes — never refactor unrelated files while fixing a bug
